9 FLOOR SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to financial institutions; amending 6
O.S. 2021, Section 2205, which relates to the
11 Financial Privacy Act; permitting disclosure or
release of information for investigations of
12 financial exploitation of protected adults; defining
terms; requiring employees of certain institutions to
13 notify the institution of suspected financial
exploitation of a protected adult; directing certain
14 institution to notify proper agency; permitting
certain institution to notify trusted contact of
15 suspected financial exploitation of a protected
adult; authorizing temporary holds; requiring
16 provision of certain notice of temporary hold;
requiring provision of certain timeline for temporary
17 hold; exempting notice to trusted contact if contact
is suspected of financial exploitation of the
18 protected adult; providing immunity for certain
institution and employees for compliance with
19 section; requiring retention of certain records;
permitting access to certain records upon
20 certification by an agency that an investigation into
financial exploitation of a protected adult is being
21 undertaken by the agency; authorizing certain
statement containing financial information during
22 certain time frame; requiring requests to comply with
the Financial Privacy Act; providing for
23 codification; and providing an effective date.
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 1

1
2 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
3 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 6 O.S. 2021, Section 2205, is
4 amended to read as follows:
5 Section 2205. A. Nothing in the Financial Privacy Act shall
6 prohibit the disclosure or release of any financial record or
7 information to any supervisory agency in the exercise of its
8 supervisory or regulatory functions with respect to a financial
9 institution.
10 B. Nothing in the Financial Privacy Act prohibits a financial
11 institution from disclosing or releasing any financial record or
12 information to another financial institution for the usual and
13 regular business purposes of the latter or from providing copies of
14 any financial record to any court or government authority as an
15 incident to perfecting a security interest, proving a claim in
16 bankruptcy, or otherwise collecting on a debt either owed the
17 financial institution itself or owed the financial institution in
18 its role as a fiduciary.
19 C. Nothing in the Financial Privacy Act prohibits a financial
20 institution from notifying a government authority that such
21 institution or an officer, employee, or agent of such institution
22 has information that may be relevant to a possible violation of any
23 statute or regulation.
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 2

1 D. Sections 2201 through 2204 of this title shall not apply to
2 any court order or subpoena issued in connection with proceedings
3 before a multicounty grand jury, except that a court shall have
4 authority to order a financial institution, on which a multicounty
5 grand jury subpoena for customer records has been served, not to
6 notify the customer of the existence of the subpoena or information
7 that has been furnished to the multicounty grand jury. The court
8 may order that the customer not be notified only if it finds:
9 1. That the requested records are relevant to an ongoing
10 criminal investigation being conducted by the multicounty grand
11 jury; and
12 2. That disclosure of the existence or issuance of, or
13 compliance with the subpoena may frustrate or impede the
14 investigation.
15 E. Nothing in the Financial Privacy Act shall prohibit the
16 disclosure or release of any financial record or information as
17 required by Section 2 of this act.
18 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3401 of Title 6, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. As used in this section:
22 1. “Account” means any account of a financial institution or
23 trust business for which a protected adult has the authority to
24 transact business;
Req. No. 3724 Page 3

1 2. “Agency” means one or more of the following:
2 a. the Department of Human Services,
3 b. the office of the district attorney in the county in
4 which the suspected exploitation occurred, or
5 c. any state or federal law enforcement agency with
6 jurisdiction over the area in which the suspected
7 exploitation occurred;
8 3. “Financial exploitation” means:
9 a. the wrongful or unauthorized taking, withholding,
10 appropriation, or use of money, assets, or property of
11 a protected adult, or
12 b. any act or omission taken by a person, including
13 through the use of a power of attorney, guardianship,
14 conservatorship, or any other authority, regarding a
15 protected adult, to:
16 (1) obtain control, through the use of intimidation,
17 undue influence, coercion, harassment, duress,
18 deception, false representation, or false
19 pretense, over the protected adult’s money,
20 assets, or property, or
21 (2) convert or divert money, assets, or property of
22 the protected adult to deprive the protected
23 adult of the ownership, use, benefit, or
24 possession of the money, assets, or property;
Req. No. 3724 Page 4

1 4. “Financial institution” has the same meaning as defined in
2 Section 2202 of Title 6 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
3 5. “Institution” means a financial institution or trust
4 business;
5 6. “Protected adult” means:
6 a. an individual sixty-two (62) years of age or older, or
7 b. an incapacitated person or a vulnerable adult as such
8 terms are defined in the Protective Services for
9 Vulnerable Adults Act;
10 7. “Trust business” means the same as defined in Section 1702
11 of Title 6 of the Oklahoma Statutes; and
12 8. “Trusted contact” means any adult person designated by a
13 customer of an institution that the institution may contact in the
14 event of an emergency or loss of contact with the customer, or in
15 the event of suspected third-party fraud or financial exploitation
16 targeting the customer.
17 B. If an employee of an institution reasonably believes that
18 financial exploitation of a protected adult in this state has
19 occurred, is occurring, has been attempted, is being attempted, or
20 will be attempted, the employee shall notify the institution of the
21 suspected financial exploitation. If the institution reasonably
22 believes that financial exploitation has occurred or is occurring,
23 the institution shall promptly notify one or more of the proper
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 5

1 agen cies pursuant to the provisions of the Protective Services for
2 Vulnerable Adults Act.
3 C. If an institution believes that financial exploitation of a
4 protected adult has occurred, is occurring, has been attempted, is
5 being attempted, or will be attempted, in or from this state, the
6 institution may notify the trusted contact, or in the absence of
7 such designation, any other third party that the institution
8 reasonably believes is associated with the protected adult.
9 D. 1. An institution transacting business in or from this
10 state with a protected adult may place a temporary hold on a
11 transaction with or a disbursement of funds from an account of such
12 protected adult or an account on which such protected adult is a
13 beneficiary if:
14 a. the institution believes that financial exploitation
15 of a protected adult has occurred, is occurring, has
16 been attempted, is being attempted, or will be
17 attempted, and
18 b. the institution:
19 (1) immediately, but in no event more than three (3)
20 business days after the date the temporary hold
21 is first placed, provides oral or written
22 notification, which may be electronic, of the
23 temporary hold and the reason to all parties
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 6

1 authorized to transact business with the account
2 and to any trusted contact, and
3 (2) immediately initiates an internal review of the
4 suspected or attempted financial exploitation of
5 the protected adult, as necessary.
6 2. An agency or a court of competent jurisdiction may terminate
7 or extend a temporary hold authorized by this subsection. Any
8 temporary hold of a transaction or disbursement of funds as
9 authorized by this subsection shall expire upon the earlier of:
10 a. a determination by the institution that the
11 transaction or disbursement of funds shall not result
12 in financial exploitation of the protected adult, or
13 b. not later than ten (10) business days after the date
14 on which the institution first placed the temporary
15 hold on the transaction or disbursement of funds,
16 unless the institution’s internal review of the facts
17 and circumstances supports the institution’s
18 reasonable belief that financial exploitation of the
19 protected adult has occurred, is occurring, has been
20 attempted, or will be attempted, or the institution
21 receives a request for an extension by one or more of
22 the agencies, in which case the institution may extend
23 the temporary hold to not later than twenty (20)
24 business days after the date the institution first
Req. No. 3724 Page 7

1 placed the temporary hold on the transaction or
2 disbursement of the funds.
3 3. Nothing in this subsection shall require an institution to
4 place a temporary hold on any transaction with or disbursement of
5 funds from an account of a protected adult or an account on which
6 such protected adult is a beneficiary.
7 E. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsections C and D of
8 this section, a notification permitted or required by this section
9 shall not be made to any person the institution reasonably believes
10 has engaged, is engaging, or will engage in suspected or attempted
11 financial exploitation of the protected adult.
12 F. 1. An institution, or any employee of an institution, who
13 makes a notification or report under subsection B of this section,
14 makes a notification or report to a third party under subsection C
15 of this section, provides records to any agency pursuant to
16 subsection G of this section, or testifies or otherwise participates
17 in a judicial proceeding arising from such notification, report, or
18 provision of records, shall be immune from any civil or criminal
19 liability arising from the notification, report, provision of
20 records, testimony, or participation in the judicial proceeding,
21 unless the employee or institution acted in bad faith or with a
22 malicious purpose.
23 2. An institution that places, releases, or does not place a
24 hold on any transaction pursuant to subsection D of this section
Req. No. 3724 Page 8

1 shal l be immune from any civil or criminal liability, as well as any
2 disciplinary action from the Banking Department, from that action or
3 failure to act, unless the institution acted in bad faith or with a
4 malicious purpose.
5 G. An institution shall retain and, to the extent permitted by
6 state and federal law, may provide access to or copies of records
7 that are relevant to the suspected or attempted financial
8 exploitation of a protected adult to any agency upon the written
9 certification of the agency that an investigation into the financial
10 exploitation of a protected adult is being undertaken by the agency.
11 Upon such certification, the agency may request an institution to
12 furnish, and an institution may, but shall not be required to,
13 furnish, a statement setting forth the following information with
14 respect to a customer account specified by the requesting party for
15 a period of ninety (90) days before and up to sixty (60) days
16 following the date of occurrence of the alleged illegal act
17 involving the account:
18 1. The number of items dishonored;
19 2. The number of items paid that created overdrafts;
20 3. The dollar volume of the dishonored items and items paid
21 which created overdrafts and a statement explaining any credit
22 arrangement between the bank, credit union, or savings association
23 and customer to pay overdrafts;
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 9

1 4. The dates and amounts of deposits and debits and the account
2 balance;
3 5. A copy of the signature card, including the signature and
4 any addresses appearing on a customer’s signature card;
5 6. New bank cards issued;
6 7. Change of address requests received;
7 8. Power of attorney or trust documents submitted or executed;
8 9. The date the account opened and, if applicable, the date the
9 account closed; and
10 10. Surveillance photographs and video recordings of persons
11 accessing the victim’s financial account via an automated teller
12 machine (ATM) or from within the institution for dates on which
13 illegal acts involving the account were alleged to have occurred.
14 This paragraph shall not be construed to:
15 a. require an institution to produce a photograph or
16 video recording if the institution does not possess
17 the photograph or video recording, or
18 b. affect any existing civil immunities under state law.
19 A bank, credit union, or savings association that provides the
20 requesting party with copies of one or more complete account
21 statements prepared in the regular course of business shall be
22 deemed to be in compliance with paragraphs 1 through 4 of this
23 subsection.
24
Req. No. 3724 Page 10

1 H. Any request for information from an agency, not including
2 the provisions of this section, shall comply with the Financial
3 Privacy Act. Nothing in subsection G of this section shall be
4 construed to prohibit an institution from requiring the agencies to
5 comply with the Financial Privacy Act.
6 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
